<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="1580" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1580">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.62/62.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">German Chargé
                                        d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">German Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-27">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 27, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Nürnberg</hi> has been ordered from the West Coast
                                of Mexico to Panama for the purpose of exchanging <pb facs="1004" n="888" xml:id="pg_888"/> its personnel. By direction of the
                                Imperial Government, I have the honor to request your kind
                                intervention that the Government of the United States may direct the
                                American naval vessels to assume the protection of German interests
                                on the Mexican west coast during the absence of H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Nürnberg</hi>.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kurt von Lersner</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>